file-name: XC420173- синица (Aegithalos caudatus) и зяблик (Fringilla coelebs). 12.06.2018.mp3

rmk: This recording was made by placing the recorder in the flight path of a pair of nest-building Long-tailed Tits.  I left the recorder for about 90 minutes, then I retrieved it and edited the sounds. The birds were constructing a nest in downtown Belfast.  Imagine the racket! Hence I tried to capture calls early on a Sunday morning (when everyone was at church ... ).  Long-tailed Tits use three sounds. They also have a song but I have never heard it. In any event - according to books - the song is feeble and only used when birds are in fairly close proximity. Being social by nature, they generally are in close proximity. Little wonder, therefore, that the song is 'for their ears only'.  But let's get back to their three types of calls. First, there is a rolling, almost chirruping sound that sounds quite like the word 'stirrup'. As in most of their utterances, repetition is habitual - so the 'stirrup' is usually given in a sequence. You can hear it repeatedly from 0:04 up to the twenty-third second.  Second, there is a Goldcrest-like 'zee' (repeated in a short series). The zee can be doubled, trebled or quadrupled. Interestingly, when trebled or (especially) quadrupled, the final note in just slightly lower-pitched (this sounds really esoteric but once you listen, you can notice the minor fall in pitch).  I have edited the recording to keep the 'stirrup' calls at the start and then bring in a sequence of 'zee' calls. By luck, the first zee series (0:26) has two notes; the second zee series (0:28) has three notes; the third zee series (0:30) has four notes. From here to the end of the clip, you can count the number of zee notes yourself. Finally, a single 'tap' (or a hard, tacking note) permeates their vocabulary. The tap is given more randomly than either the 'stirrup' or 'zee'. You can hear 'taps' at the very beginning (just after 0:03) before the first 'stirrup' calls.  Other clear taps can be heard at 0:12 (for the next two seconds).  Often a group of Long-tailed Tits moving through cover will use these tapping notes. When that happens - pretty often, during winter - the effect feels like being caught out in a sonic hail shower.  Other calls in the recording are WOODPIGEON (full song cycle from 0:24) and nosy-parker churring from a pair of GREAT TITS at 1:12 and (both birds) 1:21 during the next two seconds.  Other - more pleasant - calls are given by the same Great Tits on other parts of the clip. A ROBIN sings - just one blast - at the very start (0:01) . The gulls in the background are Lesser Black-backed Gulls.
